(180, 'vi', 'Tại sao chim có thể làm rơi máy bay ', 'Chiếc Airbus 320 của Mỹ hôm nay lao xuống sông New York với nguyên nhân ban đầu được xác định là do đàn ngỗng trời đâm phải. Vậy làm thế nào những con chim trời yếu ớt có thể hạ gục một con chim sắt khổng lồ?', 'upload/images/180.jpg', '2009-01-19', '<table cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" width=\"1\" align=\"center\" border=\"0\">	<tbody>		<tr>			<td>				<img height=\"326\" alt=\"Ảnh: abcnews.com.\" src=\"http://vnexpress.net/Files/Subject/3B/A0/A7/D9/an.jpg\" width=\"441\" /></td>		</tr>		<tr>			<td class=\"Image\">Chim dễ bị hút vào động cơ khi đâm trúng máy bay. Ảnh: <em>abcnews.com</em>.</td>		</tr>	</tbody></table><p class=\"Normal\">Máy bay bị chim đâm phải diễn ra hàng ngày trên khắp thế giới, nhưng không phải vụ nào cũng gây ra tai nạn. Kể từ năm 1988 đến nay có hơn 200 người chết trong các vụ tai nạn máy bay liên quan tới động vật, gây thiệt hại hơn 600 triệu USD mỗi năm. Riêng trong năm 2007 không quân Mỹ thống kê có hơn 5.000 vụ va chạm giữa máy bay và chim trên lãnh thổ nước này. </p><p class=\"SubTitle\">Nguy hiểm do chênh lệch tốc độ</p><p class=\"Normal\">Phần lớn vụ va chạm xảy ra khi máy bay gần mặt đất, thời điểm cất cánh hoặc hạ cánh. Va chạm giữa chim trời và chim sắt có thể biến thành tai nạn nghiêm trọng nếu các con chim lớn thuộc các loài như ngỗng trời, kền kền và mòng biển bị hút vào động cơ phản lực, làm gãy cánh quạt khiến động cơ ngừng hoạt động. </p><p class=\"Normal\">Vụ tai nạn tại New York sáng nay xảy ra ngay sau khi chiếc Airbus A320 của hãng US Airways cất cánh từ sân bay LaGuardia với 155 hành khách và phi hành đoàn. Các nguồn tin cho rằng máy bay đâm phải một đàn ngỗng trước khi hạ cạnh xuống mặt sông và điều thần kỳ xảy ra là không có ai thiệt mạng. </p><p class=\"Normal\">Về mặt lý thuyết các máy bay lớn có thể tiếp tục bay sau khi va chạm với chim nặng tối đa 2 kg. Tuy nhiên, có tới 36 loài chim tại Bắc Mỹ có trọng lượng trung bình lớn hơn thế, trong khi ngay cả những loài chim nhỏ như sáo đá cũng có thể làm hỏng động cơ cực mạnh của máy bay.</p><p class=\"Normal\">Chênh lệch tốc độ giữa máy bay và chim càng lớn thì tác động của vụ va chạm đối với máy bay càng đáng sợ. Trọng lượng của chim cũng là một yếu tố, nhưng khác biệt tốc độ có vai trò lớn hơn. Một đàn chim sẽ trở nên nguy hiểm hơn nếu chúng đâm vào máy bay nhiều lần.</p><p class=\"Normal\">Dale Oderman, một giáo sư giảng dạy bộ môn kỹ thuật hàng không tại Đại học Purdue (Mỹ) cho biết chim là mối nguy hiểm lớn đối với phi cơ, đặc biệt là trong lúc cất cánh. “Ngỗng trời và các loài chim lớn đáng sợ hơn chim nhỏ. Khi chim va phải máy bay, chúng có thể bị hút vào động cơ và làm gãy cánh quạt. Chiếc cánh gãy bị hút sâu vào bên trong động cơ và làm hỏng các bộ phận khác”, ông nói.</p><p class=\"Normal\">Giáo sư Dale nhận định rằng, trong trường hợp của vụ tai nạn trên sông Hudson, New York sáng nay chim đã làm hỏng cả hai động cơ của chiếc Airbus A320. </p><p class=\"Normal\">Để đối phó với nguy hiểm rình rập từ động vật, các phi trường áp dụng nhiều biện pháp giảm thiểu nguy cơ va chạm giữa máy bay và chim. Chẳng hạn, người ta không trồng nhiều cây gần sân bay vì chim có thể làm tổ hoặc nghỉ ngơi trên cây. Tuy nhiên, do phi trường La Guardia New York nằm gần sông Hudson nên có rất nhiều chim bay quanh sân bay.</p><p class=\"SubTitle\">NASA cũng sợ chim trời</p><p class=\"Normal\">Trong lần phóng tàu vũ trụ Discovery của Cơ quan không gian Mỹ (NASA) vào tháng 7/2005, người ta nhìn thấy một con kền kền bay quanh bệ phóng. Với trọng lượng trung bình 1,4 đến 2,2 kg, chim kền kền có thể gây ra thảm họa nếu nó đâm vào mũi hoặc cánh của tàu con thoi trong giai đoạn cất cánh.</p><p class=\"Normal\">NASA đề ra nhiều quy định an toàn từ năm 2005 để giảm thiểu nguy cơ va chạm với chim trong những lần phóng tàu vũ trụ. Họ không muốn chim đâm vào thùng nhiên liệu của tàu trong khi cất cánh và hạ cánh, bởi sự va chạm có thể làm hỏng bộ phận cách nhiệt. Do đó trong lúc hạ cánh, NASA dùng thiết bị tạo âm thanh để xua đuổi chim khỏi đường băng.</p>', 9, 316, 0, 1, '', NULL, NULL),
(181, 'vi', 'Người hùng trong cú hạ cánh kỳ diệu ở New York', 'Vị cơ trưởng cứu 155 người trên chiếc phi cơ chở khách có 40 năm kinh nghiệm lái máy bay và làm giám đốc công ty tư vấn về an toàn. ', 'upload/images/181.jpg', '2009-01-19', '<p class=\"Normal\">Chiếc máy bay Airbus A320 của hãng hàng không US Airways vừa mới cất cánh từ sân bay ở New York thì gặp sự cố. </p><p class=\"Normal\">Cơ trưởng Chesley \"Sully\" Sullenberger, 57 tuổi, thông báo máy bay bị chim tấn công hai lần và yêu cầu được hạ cánh. Hai động cơ của chiếc máy bay này đã ngừng hoạt động vì tác động của đàn chim.</p><p class=\"Normal\">Sau khi cân nhắc các lựa chọn, cơ trưởng Sullenberger quyết định lái máy bay đáp xuống sông Hudson. Và thật tuyệt diệu, chiếc máy bay đã hạ cánh trên mặt nước. </p><p class=\"Normal\">Cơ trưởng Sullenberger từng là phi công lái máy bay chiến đấu trong Không quân Mỹ. Ông còn làm chủ tịch của Hiệp hội phi công hàng không Mỹ APLA và là chuyên gia điều tra các vụ tai nạn máy bay. Ông cũng có chứng chỉ phi công lái tàu lượn. </p><p class=\"Normal\">Thị trưởng New York Micheal Bloomberg ca ngợi \"kỹ năng hạ cánh phi thường\" của Sullenberger và gọi đây là \"điều kỳ diệu trên sông Hudson\". Ông cũng cho biết Sullenberger đã đi lại trên máy bay hai lần sau khi các hành khách đã được cứu để đảm bảo không ai bị bỏ lại.</p><p class=\"Normal\">Các đồng nghiệp của Sullenberger không ngạc nhiên về hành động quyết đoán của ông trong hoàn cảnh đầy áp lực đó. Rick Kurner, phi công của hãng US Airways, đã làm việc với Sullenberger trong 23 năm qua, nói. \"Ông ấy luôn rất chuyên nghiệp\". </p><p class=\"Normal\" align=\"right\"><strong>Hải Ninh</strong> </p>', 9, 466, 0, 1, '', NULL, NULL),
(230, 'en', 'Chaotic climate threatens food security', 'HCMC – Worsening impacts of climate change including intense typhoons, salinity intrusion, floods and droughts could threaten food security for both Vietnam and other countries if essential measures are not taken immediately, according to environmental scientists who joined the 2010 Mekong Environment and Climate Symposium.', '', '2010-04-29', '<span class=\"Content\" id=\"ctl00_cphContent_lblContentHtml\">	<p>The two-day symposium, which was organized in HCMC by the Mekong River Commission and ended on Tuesday, attracted many scientists from organizations and countries sharing the Mekong basin including Thailand, Laos, Cambodia and Vietnam.&nbsp;</p>	<p>Some scientists told the symposium that more direct negative impacts of a changing environment and climate change due to global warming were damaging fisheries, agricultural production, forestry, human health and water resources of 13 provinces in the Mekong Delta of Vietnam. </p>	<p>Aslam Perwaiz, manager of the Commission’s Flood Management Program, said that if urgent measures were not taken immediately to adapt to climate change, the delta could face a serious problem of food shortage by 2030.</p>	<p>The 13 provinces vulnerable to the annual Mekong floods are Long An, Tien Giang, Dong Thap, Ben Tre, Vinh Long, Tra Vinh, An Giang, Hau Giang, Soc Trang, Kien Giang, Bac Lieu, Ca Mau and Can Tho. </p>	<p>Perwaiz said the threats to food security in the delta could emerge by 2030 when the region’s rainfall from January to July will have decreased by around 20% compared to 1980, and by more than 25% in An Giang, Kien Giang and the entire Ca Mau Peninsula. </p>	<p>Furthermore, the reduction of rainfall together with the late arrivals of the rainy seasons will make the periods of drought fiercer. “In addition, the increasing environmental risks due to the rapid urbanization are resulting in difficulties in living conditions in the delta,” he said. </p>	<p>Nguyen Van Sanh, professor of the Mekong Delta Research and Development Institute of Can Tho University, said the Mekong Delta was considered a large wetland with rich biodiversity for food security and fishery, contributing at least 50% of total paddy output, 90% of rice output for export, 60% of total fishery output and 50% of meat and egg production supplying other regions of the country. </p>	<p>The professor said worsening impacts of climate change comprising salt intrusion, droughts and intense typhoons had been threatening the food security of Vietnam and other countries. </p>	<p>“With fiercer environmental risks in the delta, triple rice cropping will be reduced by 1.8% and double rice cropping will be reduced by 2.7% during mid-2030s.” </p>	<p>To curb the negative impacts of climate change in the region, Sanh suggested that all 13 provinces needed to immediately carry out a comprehensive regional approach for adapting to increasing environmental risks.</p>	<p>He explained that the delta must protect its biodiversity and apply new, flexible methods for agricultural and fishery production against the changing weather. </p>	<p>“If we don’t have a suitable regional approach and community-based preparedness to adapt to climate change then local farmers will be fiercely affected by worsening environmental risks in years to come.”</p></span>', 71, 174, 0, 1, '', NULL, NULL),
(231, 'en', 'Vietnam mobilizes more funds to deal with climate change', 'HCMC – The Dutch Embassy in Vietnam announced on Tuesday that its government would fund Vietnam 40 million-euro to help the country deal with climate change.', 'upload/images/231.jpg', '2010-04-29', '<p>Minister of Natural Resources and Environment Pham Khoi Nguyen told attendees at a Vietnam National Mekong Committee conference held in HCMC on Wednesday that the majority of the fund would go towards projects that fight negative impacts of climate change in the Mekong Delta. 	<img align=\"right\" src=\"http://english.thesaigontimes.vn/App_Themes/Default/Imgs/SGTO_ADVERTISING.jpg\" alt=\"Vị trí đặt quảng cáo\" class=\"SGTOADV\" /></p><p>He added that under the Government’s instruction, the ministry had already mobilized sponsored funds worth US$500 million from other countries and organizations to deal with the issue. </p><p>According to the National Mekong Committee’s latest report, Vietnam will suffer more than other countries from rising sea levels in the future. </p><p>“We must do everything in our power to save the Mekong Delta from impacts of climate change,” Nguyen said.<br />	Salinity intrusion and droughts are already affecting the region, and as such, Nguyen said that funds should be prioritized to adapt to climate change, especially in 13 Mekong Delta provinces, and another four in the Central Highlands. </p><p>The ministry will coordinate with the Ministry of Planning and Investment and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs from 2011 to 2015 to mobilize more funds, estimated at between US$3.5 billion to US$5 billion to build dykes and dams and to reforest the delta, according to Nguyen. </p><p>“The Mekong Delta has endured fierce salinity intrusion and drought over the last 50 years,” he said, adding that national committee members should begin developing programs and plans to adapt to climate change in each locality. </p><p>At the conference, members of the committee including 13 provincial and city leaders in the delta and four provinces in the Highlands including Dak Lak, Dak Nong, Kon Tum and Gia Lai said that climate change had affected agricultural and fishery production in the respective regions. </p><p>Pham Hoang Be, Bac Lieu Province’s vice chairman, said that due to current salt intrusion and drought, farmers in the region are facing more difficulties in agricultural and fishery production than ever. </p><p>“Now, 11,000 hectares of farm land in Bac Lieu has been directly affected by salt intrusion and drought. About 6,000 hectares of paddy rice was completely damaged as farmers are waiting for rain,” he said. </p><p>Be added that of the province’s total 100,000 hectares of shrimp breeding area, some 20% had been damaged by changing weather. </p><p>Nguyen said that the Government would issue a national program to protect and use water sources in the delta to provide long-term sustainable measures to help the region cope with negative climate change affects. </p><p>In addition, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development is also developing another scheme for irrigation development in the Mekong Delta, planned for 2030 with a vision to 2050.</p>', 71, 69, 1, 1, 'vietnam', NULL, NULL),
(232, 'en', 'Ministry told to monitor environment at hydropower plants', 'HCMC – The Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment has just been urged by the Government to monitor environmental impact at hydropower projects that are under construction nationwide, said Deputy Minister Nguyen Thai Lai. ', '', '2010-05-04', '<p>Lai said last week that Deputy Prime Minister Hoang Trung Hai had asked the ministry to make closer inspections at hydropower plants and impose heavier fines on developers who fail to reforest after construction or that contribute to disturbing water flow in damned rivers’ lower sections. </p><p>According to the Ministry of Industry and Trade, the development of some hydropower projects in Central Vietnam and the Central Highlands has negatively affected the regions, both environmentally and socially. </p><p>Some hydropower project developers have reluctantly obeyed environment protection and dam security regulations. </p><p>“Developers of all approved hydropower projects must submit environmental impact assessments before they begin construction; however many developers have ignored the requirements,” Lai said, adding that many barely took notice of the Ministry’s appraisal and the potential consequences before building dams and reservoirs. </p><p>To protect water sources in the rivers where there are dams, Lai said that the Government had just issued a decree on the overall management of irrigation reservoirs and hydropower plants to reduce negative environmental impacts and pollution as well as to maintain normal river flows. </p><p>According to the Ministry of Industry and Trade, the country currently has 1,021 large and small hydropower projects in 36 provinces and cities with a total capacity of 24,246 MW. These hydropower projects have the potential to produce 100 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity each year.&nbsp;&nbsp; </p><p>Most of approved hydropower projects are located at ten main river basins around the country including Da, Lo-Gam-Chay, Ma-Chu, Ca, Vu Gia-Thu Bon, Tra Khuc-Huong, Se San, Ba, Serepok and Dong Nai. </p><p>The Dong Nai river basin in particular, which crosses 11 provinces and cities, has a total 17 hydropower projects under construction with a total designed capacity of 3,000 MW. </p><p>According to a study recently conducted by&nbsp;the Southern Institute for Water Resources Planning, the massive development of hydropower plants along the Dong Nai river basin has reduced its water quality. Many of the basin’s sections, especially the river’s lower reaches, are now partially polluted. </p><p>The institute said that hydropower project construction in all eleven provinces and cities was unmethodical and had ignored overall plans for regional irrigation, river flow, flood control and salinity prevention. </p><p>Meanwhile, recent research conducted by the Institute of Tropical Biology also showed that the construction of dams and reservoirs along the Dong Nai river basin had obstructed the fish population’s natural migration. </p><p>Some 300 fish varieties live in the river basin – about 30% of the country’s total freshwater fish. </p><p>The obstruction has reduced both fish variety and population in the Dong Nai River, while pollution has also affected biodiversity and habitats.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 71, 324, 1, 1, '', NULL, NULL),
(233, 'en', 'Environmental Protection: From Theory To Action', 'Commitments to joint actions against climate change and seeking renewable energy sources were released by top officials of Vietnam and Germany, international organizations and enterprises at an economic conference held in HCM City last week', '', '2010-05-06', '<span class=\"Content\" id=\"ctl00_cphContent_lblContentHtml\">	<p>When the Vietnam-Germany economic conference entitled Climate Change and Energy that was held for the first time ended, participants received special gifts before leaving. They were two power-saving fluorescent bulbs and environmental protection documents. Some people possibly wondered that these would have been common gifts like bags, USB flash drives or even mobile phones (Siemens is the main sponsor of the event). An acceptable reason was that the gifts were aimed to remind the enterprises and officials of the two countries of what they had listened to or what they had committed to during the conference.</p>	<p>At the conference, German Ambassador to Vietnam Rolf Schulze read remarks by Gerhard Schroeder, former German chancellor, who could not join the event because of the volcano ash problem in Europe. In the letter, Schroeder mentioned that climate change and renewable energy sources have had effects not only on society and ecology but also on economies and geopolitics worldwide. Floods, desertification and extreme climate conditions are visible problems. Moreover, global average temperature is going to rise 5.8 degrees Celsius. All these have had serious impacts on millions of people in the world. The former chancellor took Typhoon Ketsana that happened in Vietnam last September as an example of the climate change problem. He calls for a necessary international agreement in reducing the greenhouse effect by more sustainable energy policies and investment into new energy sources that have a little impact on the environment.</p>	<p>Vu Huy Hoang, Vietnam’s Minister of Industry and Trade, shared that given the current usage of energy sources, Vietnam will have to import fuels in the near future. At present, Vietnam is one of the five countries with the rise of sea level, salinity intrusion and land erosion. Besides self motions, Vietnam needs support from other countries, including Germany.</p>	<p>In the panel discussion between officials and businesses of the two countries, when asked about detailed figures about impacts on climate change of Vietnam, Hoang said that when the sea level rises one meter, salinity will submerge some 20,000 square kilometers of the Mekong Delta. This is a worrisome figure as the Mekong Delta is one of two main rice baskets of Vietnam.</p>	<p>The German Government is committed to helping Vietnam in transfer of technology and knowledge on energy. They also grant ODA to Vietnam for environmental activities.</p>	<p>Hoang said Vietnam has plans to produce new energy sources. It hopes that by 2020, new energy sources will make up 9-10% of the total national electricity. However, investment costs and prices of the new power sources are much higher than traditional ones. Therefore, the Government must have support for private investors into the sector.</p>	<p>During the panel discussion, some Vietnamese enterprises expressed that they need support from the Government in their energy-saving application and environmental protection in manufacturing.</p>	<p>Mai Huy Tan, general director of Duc-Viet Foods Joint Stock Co., said that his company had used the solar energy for the 4,000-square-meter plant. It is building another plant that will use biogas for production. Tan said that long-term applications will help his company save money given higher and higher traditional electricity prices.</p>	<p>A woman representative of AITS, a non-government environmental organization, said that awareness is most important. How to help Vietnamese people improve their behaviors on environmental protection is the necessary thing to do.</p>	<p>Her opinion was partly suitable with the purposes of presenting the aforementioned gifts. They were good tools to remind the conference participants, half of them Vietnamese people, of environmental protection. </p></span>', 71, 411, 1, 1, '', NULL, NULL),
(234, 'en', 'Lower Water Levels Spell Trouble', 'Over 20 major hydropower plants, with a combined capacity of 6,200MW, must restrict output at 50 million kWh per day until the end of the hot season. This translates into merely eight hours of operation when the plants are at full throttle, which is rather dismal.', 'upload/images/234.jpg', '2010-05-06', '<p>The Ba Ha River hydropower plant only holds enough water to generate electricity for three hours per day. New plants such as Cua Dat and Ban Ve have stored water since 2009, but the volumes held are inadequate for 72 hours of operation. The power shortage will amount to 500 million kWh per month because the unexpected dry spell will probably persist in months to come.</p><p>Although the Electricity of Vietnam Group (EVN) has anticipated this problem since the end of the flood season in 2009, it still has to spend VND2 trillion purchasing expensive electricity, oil-fueled or otherwise, from Yunnan, China (about 4.1 billion kWh in 2010). However, it is not easy to import power as the supply from Yunnan has been temporarily stopped for maintenance purposes.</p><p>The national weather forecasting center says that the inclement weather during the dry months in 2009 and 2010, triggered by El Niño and droughts, has caused water levels from north to south to plunge to historic lows. Saltwater intrusion has also been more severe.</p><p>China’s hydropower plants have altered water flows in Vietnam, exacerbating the water shortage in 2009-2010. In fact, the water levels and flows discharged at locations near the border with China (the Da River in Muong Te, Lai Chau, the Nam Na River in Nam Giang, the Thao River in Lao Cai, the Lo River in Ha Giang, and the Gam River in Bac Me) vary drastically within a single day. Observations from locals further attest to the adverse impacts of reservoirs in China on water flows in Vietnam. In Ha Giang, many fish have already died as a result of these deleterious hydropower dams.</p><p>Another problem is that China’s hydropower dams store water but do not release it when Vietnam is faced with a shortage. The demise of protective forests, which can hold substantial amounts of water, has aggravated matters. It is no longer possible to row a boat in several rivers during the dry season.</p><p>Besides, hydropower plants did not start storing water early enough. Although Dang Hoang An, deputy general director of EVN, says that the group has made efforts to minimize water use, the weather forecasting center says that they are far from sufficient. In fact, while China’s hydropower plants often begin storing water in mid-July, Vietnam’s start only on August 20. Without suitable remedies, water flows to the Da River and the Lo River may shrink further, and future dry seasons will probably arrive sooner.</p><p>A solution is not enough to quench Vietnam’s thirst for water in 2010. However, it will at least help reduce the waste incurred by costly hydropower plants. </p>', 71, 86, 1, 1, '', NULL, NULL);
